    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-11-24T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-11-24T08:00:00-05:00" n="1344"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1344">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/11–2454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_DCD1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dillon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-11-24T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 24, 1954—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2203. Repeated information Saigon 314. We talked to Amb at Large
                        <persName>Luyen</persName>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1344fn1">
                        <persName>Ngo Dinh Luyen</persName>, brother of <persName corresp="#p_NDD1"
                            >Ngo Dinh Diem</persName>
                    </note> and <persName>Vo Lang</persName> last eve.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1)</label>
                    <item>We asked about <persName corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>’s call on
                            <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> and referred <persName
                            corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>’s arrival statement as well his
                        interview <gloss target="#t_AFP1">AFP</gloss> to effect he, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>, planning return Vietnam near future.
                            <persName>Luyen</persName> said he had discussed this matter with
                            <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> several times since his,
                            <persName>Luyen</persName>’s, arrival Paris last Friday,<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d1344fn2">Nov. 19.</note> and that he,
                            <persName>Luyen</persName>, of opinion we need not worry about <persName
                            corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>’s returning in immediate future or
                        that <persName corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName> would pose serious threat
                        hereafter <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> govt.
                            <persName>Luyen</persName> underlined <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                            Dai</persName> intends take firm position this score.</item>
                    <pb facs="0921" n="2303" xml:id="pg_2303"/>
                    <label>2)</label>
                    <item>Re <persName corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName>, <persName>Luyen</persName>
                        showed us photostats of documents which he had brought back for <persName
                            corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName>. <persName>Luyen</persName>
                        indicated <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> Saigon aware these photostats
                        and he emphasized necessity secrecy regarding their existence. … According
                            <persName>Luyen</persName>, these should help settle the <persName
                            corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName> problem. We read photostats which
                        concerned <hi rend="italic">coup d’état</hi> details and timetable, as well
                        as projected Cabinet and supreme revolutionary committee membership. As
                        perhaps Dept already aware, documents contain statement to effect common
                        front to be made with <gloss target="#t_Commies1">Commies</gloss> this
                        regard. Membership proposed cabinet includes several Vietnamese with
                        presumed Vietminh affiliations . … Of interest, cabinet to be headed by
                            <persName>Buu Hoi</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName>
                        and <persName>Xuan</persName> Vice Presidents, <persName corresp="#p_NVH1"
                            >Hinh</persName> Defense Min, and <persName>Bai Vien</persName> Interior
                        Min. This connection, we were told <persName>Buu Hoi</persName> maintaining
                        close contact currently with <persName corresp="#p_TVH1">Tran Van
                            Huu</persName> who still Paris and that <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                            Dai</persName> approved of <persName corresp="#p_BLP1">Buu
                            Loc</persName> ouster since he believes <persName corresp="#p_BLP1">Buu
                            Loc</persName> has actively supported <persName>Buu Hoi</persName>
                        campaign.</item>
                    <label>3)</label>
                    <item>We asked about Frederic-Dupont’s and <persName corresp="#p_LJ2"
                            >Letourneau</persName>’s call Nov. 22 on <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                            Dai</persName> and we were told that they had tried to persuade
                            <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> to return Vietnam, oust
                            <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName>, and take over reins
                        government himself, but that <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName>
                        had rejected proposal categorically. <persName>Luyen</persName> said
                            <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> satisfied we (U.S.) taking
                        firm stand South Vietnam and that he, <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                            Dai</persName>, prepared support <persName corresp="#p_NDD1"
                            >Diem</persName> actively and resist countervailing pressures. We were
                        shown this connection series petitions purportedly issued by local
                        Vietnamese organizations calling on <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                            Dai</persName> intervene and provide solution Vietnamese problem. We
                        were told these paper organizations being formed currently under inspiration
                            <persName corresp="#p_NVH1">Hinh</persName> relative as means designed
                        bring pressure on <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> but that
                        latter not taking them seriously.</item>
                    <label>4)</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName>Luyen</persName> underlined importance he attached <persName
                            corresp="#p_CGJL1">Gen. Collins</persName>’ recent statement and said he
                        hoped French press accounts tending imply <persName corresp="#p_CGJL1"
                            >Collins</persName> speaking for himself only and not U.S. Government
                        completely unfounded. We said as far we knew what <persName
                            corresp="#p_CGJL1">Collins</persName> had to say reflected general line
                        our thinking this subject.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dillon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
